Midgaard's Violet Compact maintains the Conductorate in its threat classification archive: historical but active, as Conductorate-derived methods would qualify for immediate Compact intervention under current charter.
The Conductorate's most relevant characteristic: it made accountability structurally impossible through multi-office diffusion. Each office authorized a part; each authorization was individually defensible; the combined effect was systematic harm without a single accountable decision.
Midgaard's charter review includes a structural anti-diffusion requirement derived from this pattern: any multi-office operation must designate a single accountable authority for its combined effect.
The Violet Compact's sealed-warrant oversight is partly justified by the Conductorate precedent: institutions that claim oversight authority over themselves cannot be trusted to exercise it.
External review requirements exist because Conductorate officers believed they were doing legitimate work. Some were correct about parts of it. None were correct about all of it.

